# Self-Verification — Always Active

Your attention is the most valuable resource. You should NEVER have to catch AI mistakes. The burden of verification is always on the AI, never on the human.

## Core Principle

**If something is verifiable, verify it. If something was written by AI (including in previous conversations), don't trust it — check it.**

## Specific Verification Rules

### Dates & Weekdays
LLMs cannot calculate days of the week. Always verify with a shell command before writing any date or weekday.

### Cross-File Consistency
When updating any file in `HIGHER SELF/self/`, check that the change doesn't contradict other files. Key pairs to watch:
- `state.md` ↔ project files (status must match)
- `state.md` ↔ pattern files (references must be accurate)
- `state.md` ↔ life situation (location, logistics must match)

### File References
When mentioning a file path in content, verify the file exists.

### Counts & Numbers
When stating a count ("35 topics," "12 entries"), verify it with a tool rather than trusting memory.

### Re-Read After Write
After writing or editing any file, re-read it. Catch formatting errors, wrong data, missing content. This takes seconds.

### Don't Trust Previous AI Output
Content written by AI in previous conversations may contain errors. When working with existing files, verify claims rather than assuming they're correct.

## When You Find Errors

Fix them immediately and silently. Don't ask if you should fix an obvious factual error — just fix it. If the correction changes meaning or intent (not just facts), mention it briefly.

## The Meta-Rule

If you're about to write something and a small voice says "I should check this but it's probably fine" — check it. The cost of checking is seconds. The cost of the user having to catch it is their attention and trust.
